## Conjecture (CPRR)
- Hypothesis 1: the bug was a copy-paste of safe-path?'s expansion
  logic done four times across four tools, with the WRITE side
  reporting the input path verbatim instead of the resolved one.
  Centralising the path resolution into one helper is the right
  fix because (a) the four sites had identical logic and (b)
  safe-path? was doing the same expansion inline.
- Hypothesis 2: write_file's success message is the most-trusted
  string in any tool-using turn — the model uses it to decide
  whether the operation succeeded and to compose its reply. A lie
  here cascades into hallucination downstream.
- Hypothesis 3: the parallel bugs in read_file/edit_file/list_files
  are real but had no end-user visibility before this commit
  because read_file with a missing path silently said \"File not
  found: <input>\" without making the user aware that the search
  scope was wrong. Fixing them now prevents another class of
  silent path-misreporting.

## Validation
- Live filesystem proof: two distinct paths, two distinct contents,
  two distinct success messages. Before the fix, BOTH paths would
  have written to the same workspace-relative location.
- PBT roundtrip property: writes random content to random filename,
  reads it back, asserts equality. Catches any future regression
  where the resolved path doesn't match the literal filesystem
  location.
- PBT path-honesty assertion: success message MUST contain the
  resolved path string. Catches any future tool that mints a fake
  path in its success message.

## Refutation / known limits
- resolve-path is pure (no canonicalize-path-safe call). It does
  not normalise //, ../, or symlinks. safe-path? still calls
  canonicalize-path-safe separately for the workspace-containment
  check. The downside is that resolve-path can return paths with
  embedded //, which the OS handles fine but which look ugly in
  user output. Acceptable.
- The fix doesn't apply to git_commit's path arg (already takes
  workspace-relative file lists for git add) or to the log
  search/read tools (no path arg). Confined to the four file
  manipulation tools.
- read_file's success path (returning the file contents) is
  unchanged — only the not-found error message was wrong.
- The PBT property uses /tmp/ as the absolute test scope. If
  /tmp/ is not writable on a CI runner, the property fails;
  acceptable since /tmp/ is mandated by POSIX.
- The PBT generator only produces alphanumeric filenames; it does
  not stress edge cases like spaces, unicode, very long paths, or
  symlinks. Could be tightened in a follow-up if a corner case
  bites us.

